Many project managers often face the following problems:

1. Lack of project management knowledge and skills, relying solely on personal experience and without a solid theoretical foundation;
2. Absence of a systematic project management process and support system, making it difficult to implement project management in practice;
3. Inaccurate project estimation, insufficient monitoring and control, and poor coordination among team members;
4. Unclear role distribution and handling of "old-hand" issues in the team, hindering cross-departmental collaboration and project progress;
5. Difficulty in communicating and coordinating with other departments, leading to slow project advancement.
